{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"152e0eef-ee06-4a64-97fe-49fc05bbc59c","content":"I can help point you in the right direction. Analyzing a `.dmp` file is a post-mortem debugging task — here are your main options:\n\n**`dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform)\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze <your-file.dmp>\n```\nUseful commands inside the REPL: `clrstack`, `pe` (print exception), `dumpheap`, `threads`.\n\n**WinDbg** (Windows)\nOpen the dump, load SOS (`.loadby sos coreclr`), then use `!pe`, `!clrstack`, `!threads`.\n\n**LLDB + SOS** (Linux/macOS)\n```bash\nlldb --core <your-file.dmp>\nplugin load libsosplugin.so\nsos PrintException\n```\n\nStart with `pe` / `PrintException` — it usually reveals the unhandled exception and stack trace that caused the crash. Would you like help with a specific tool or step?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"24474c38-301c-44e8-80cc-d321261ed4e7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze, profiling or tracing.\"\n\nSo the dump-collect skill is not appropriate here. I should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing crash dumps.","outputTokens":357,"requestId":"7644:22827A:1925200:1CB8C3E:69FE93E4"},"id":"ef70826f-8cc2-41e2-b5b7-055cfd748239","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:54:54.733Z","parentId":"36c0dcda-b19a-49f1-be65-855a55c0b52a"}
